<h2>Solar Panels in Kentucky</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Kentucky receives approximately 4.3 peak sun hours per day on average, with significant seasonal variation that affects solar production throughout the year. During peak summer months (June-August), the state can see up to 5.5-6.0 peak sun hours daily, while winter months (December-February) typically provide 2.5-3.5 peak sun hours. This seasonal variation means that a typical residential solar system in Kentucky will generate 65-70% of its annual production during the six-month period from April through September.</p>

<p>The state's solar irradiance levels average around 4.2-4.6 kWh/m¬≤/day, which places Kentucky in the middle tier of U.S. states for solar potential. While not as sunny as southwestern states, Kentucky's solar resource is more than adequate for cost-effective solar installations. A typical 6kW residential system in Kentucky can be expected to produce approximately 7,500-8,500 kWh annually, depending on system orientation, tilt angle, and local shading conditions. South-facing installations with minimal shading and optimal tilt angles (around 35-37 degrees) will achieve the highest production levels.</p>

<p>Geographic variations within Kentucky also affect solar production potential. Western Kentucky generally receives slightly higher solar irradiance than eastern regions, with areas around Paducah and Henderson seeing some of the state's best solar resources. However, even in the mountainous eastern regions, solar installations remain economically viable, particularly when combined with Kentucky's net metering policies that allow homeowners to receive full retail credit for excess solar production fed back into the grid.</p>

