<h2>Kentucky Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Kentucky homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The most substantial incentive is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations completed through 2032. This credit applies to the full cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to a \$6,000 federal tax credit that directly reduces your tax liability dollar-for-dollar.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> This comprehensive credit covers solar panels, inverters, mounting systems, wiring, and installation labor. The credit can be claimed in the year the system is installed and can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds your current tax liability. There is no maximum limit on the credit amount, making it valuable for both residential and commercial installations.</li>

<li><strong>Kentucky Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Kentucky offers a complete property tax exemption for solar energy systems installed on residential properties. This means that while your solar installation may increase your home's value by \$15,000-25,000, you won't pay additional property taxes on that increased value. This exemption continues for the life of the system, providing ongoing savings.</li>

<li><strong>Kentucky Utilities Programs:</strong> KU offers net metering for solar customers, allowing you to receive full retail credit (10.7¬¢/kWh) for excess solar electricity fed back into the grid. KU also provides rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, with rebates ranging from \$200-800 for qualifying heat pumps, smart thermostats, and ductwork improvements.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Many of Kentucky's electric cooperatives and municipal utilities offer additional rebates for energy efficiency improvements. East Kentucky Power Cooperative members can access rebates up to \$500 for heat pump installations, while many municipal utilities offer rebates for ENERGY STAR certified HVAC equipment and smart home energy management systems.</li>

<li><strong>Maximizing Incentives:</strong> To maximize available incentives, consider timing your solar and HVAC installations strategically. Installing both systems in the same tax year can help you fully utilize the federal tax credit, while utility rebates can be stacked with federal incentives for maximum savings. Working with certified installers ensures you meet all requirements for available incentive programs.</li>
</ul>

